  "text": "Innate and adaptive immune cells not only participate in tumour surveillance and antitumour immunity but can also support tumour growth [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] 74 . For example, tumour-associated macrophages facilitate the growth and metastasis of primary tumours, whereas antitumour immunity is primarily provided by CD8 + T helper cells and natural killer cells 74 . However, our current understanding of how these innate and adaptive immune cells participate in tumour growth, tumour surveillance and antitumour immunity is based on studies that were carried out in thermally stressed animals, which might not accurately reflect the functions of host immunity in tumorigenesis. In support of this suggestion, a study published in 2013 found that the growth of syngeneic and carcinogen-induced tumours was considerably delayed in mice housed at an ambient temperature of 30-31 °C compared with those housed at 22-23 °C (REF. 89 ). This delay in tumour growth was dependent on the adaptive immune system, as the delay was not observed in severe combined immunodeficient (SCID) and nude mice. Furthermore, antibody-mediated immune cell depletion experiments revealed that tumours in thermoneutral mice were infiltrated by CD8 + T helper cells, which were required for antitumour immunity 89 .",
